@normanmaurer While having fun implementing this I've found something odd by adding this test to `AbstractByteBufTest`:
```java
    @Test
    public void testEndiannessIndexOf() {
        buffer.clear();
        final int v = 1
                      | (2 << 8)
                      | (3 << 16)
                      | (2 << 24);
        buffer.writeIntLE(v);
        buffer.writeByte((byte) 1);

        assertEquals(-1, buffer.indexOf(1, 4, (byte) 1));
        assertEquals(-1, buffer.indexOf(4, 1, (byte) 1));
        assertEquals(1, buffer.indexOf(1, 4, (byte) 2));
        assertEquals(3, buffer.indexOf(4, 1, (byte) 2));
    }
```
See the test results:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13125299/97137221-99819f00-1755-11eb-89e7-4755c1c8feef.png)

I don't think is expected...or I'm not correctly using the `writeXXXLE` methods?

I can open a separate issue for this if needed

NOTE: this test is failing with the current `indexOf` implementation, not the new one!
